To my understanding, this was manufactured by a company in Santa Monica in the 70's under licensing from S&W. It was made as a simple inexpensive fire arm. The targeted buyer was often store clerks who were looking for an inexpensive way to protect the store. The quality control was not as good as if S&W was manufacturing themselves. This is meant to be a simple , easy to use revolver that will get 5 shots off.  Its not meant to take to a range and put 500 rounds through.  Hense the cheap price. Most of these guns are missing the barrel locking pin, or other parts. This hasnt been fired since 1972.  So, its in amazing condition with all parts .

title: For Sale:  BSA Royal Sporting 222
postcontent: SOLD!For Sale: Birmingham Sporting Arms Royal Sporting Rifle chambered in 222 Remington.  Also known as the Hunter, the Royal Sporting Rifle was one of the first of BSA’s first non-rimfire designs. Though it was produced for only 5 short years in the mid-to-late 1950s, it appeared in a plethora of models, firing different cartridges and with several different weights. The Royal Sporting Rifle had dovetails for a scope mount, a low Monte Carlo comb, and a raised cheekpiece on the stock. There were three models of the Royal. Short-action models (.22 Hornet and .222 Remington) had the basic features of the Royal, including a low Monte Carlo stock with a raised cheekpiece, a checkered pistol grip wrist, and a checkered fore-end. The metalwork is of natural-finish steel with a 24-inch barrel. They were not drilled and tapped for a scope mount, but had a folding-leaf rear sight.Based on the rifles serial number it was manufactured in England in March of 1955.  For a 63 year old rifle this weapon is in amazing condition.  The metal including a 24 inch barrel are in 100% condition and the wood is in approximately 90% condition exhibiting only light handling marks.  The rifle will come with a Simmons Pro Hunter scope in 6X18 by 200.  (Sling is not included)Must be willing to meet at local PD or other public arena, must possess a valid MO drivers license and must be willing to sign a bill of sale.Thank you
